        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>DR. B. FELSENTHAL&#44;<lb/>
                237 S. Desplaines Street.<lb/></p>
            <p>Chicago&#44; September 1. 1882<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. S. Morais&#44; Philadelphia.<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Sir&#58;&#45;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>I thank you sincerely for having called my attention<lb/> to the fact that Luzzatto&#39;s Hebrew correspondence is<lb/> now being published.  Though I must necessarily<lb/> restrict myself very much in buying books&#44; and so<lb/> forth&#44;&#45;&#45;for my income is but a small one&#44; and ad<lb/>vancing years <hi rend="underline">compel</hi> me to put to myself the question&#58;<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#45;&#45;yet I am such an admirer<lb/> of the immortal &#91;Hebrew&#93; that I cannot <del>th</del> withstand the<lb/> strong desire of bringing his correspondence into my<lb/> possession.  I look forward to Luzz.&#39;s correspondence<lb/> with the most eminent Jewish savants of his times in<lb/> the&#44; no doubt&#44; well founded expectation that it will<lb/> furnish exceedingly with contributions towards history<lb/> of modern Judaism in various aspects&#44; and that<lb/> we may also derive therefrom much information<lb/> on many grammatical&#44; exegetical&#44; critical&#44;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>historical points in the realm of biblical and post&#45;<lb/>biblical literature of the Jews.  I shall be obliged<lb/> to you if you will be kind enough to order the volumes<lb/> for me.<lb/></p>
            <p>I embrace this opportunity to assure you&#44; dear Sir&#44;<lb/> of my sincerest regards.  May the year &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; and a<lb/> large number of its successors&#44; prove to you to be full<lb/> of prosperity and true happiness&#44; &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours respectfully<lb/>
                B. Felsenthal<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
